<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-05-24T05:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-05-24T05:00:00-05:00" n="162" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d162">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/3277:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Bullitt</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-05-24T11:00:00+01:00">May 24,
                                    1940—11 a.m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received May 24—8:04 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>844. Your 462, May 23, noon. I delivered the President’s message to the
                            Belgian Ambassador this morning. He informed me that he would transmit
                            it at once to the Belgian Government; but that unfortunately he could
                            not communicate it to King Leopold who was cut off with the French,
                            Belgian, and British Armies now fighting on Belgian soil.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Bullitt</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>